Objects of Memory: History and Narrative
 in French War Museums
 Daniel J. Sherman
 Epitomizing the obsession with the past that is characteristic of post-
 modern culture, the museum in the broadest sense occupies a central
 place in current debates about history and memory. In its own origi-
 nal configuration the museum displayed history as, in the words of
 Eugenio Donato, "an eternally present spectacle." ' In this sense it is
 an artifact of the age of Pierre Nora's "memory-history," in which
 history devoted itself to asserting the identity of a nation's mem-
 ory with its character. Today, in Nora's view, "critical history," his
 term for the scholarly production of the last half century, seeks to
 destroy "true" memory by confining it to "sites" or lieux de memoire.
 Museums, like history, emphasize not continuity but discontinuity;
