 The importance of Nora's project notwithstanding, his over-
 all schema prompts some skepticism, not least because he relies
 on a rigid distinction between history and memory.3 Nora's chro-
 nology, moreover, which situates the history-memory antagonism in
 the period since the 1930s and posits the nineteenth century as the
 golden age of "memory-history," is open to question. Among Nora's
 lieux, the museum has been associated with the memorial virtually
 from the moment of its emergence as an institution two hundred
 years ago. The adjectival form "museal," indeed, gained currency
 through the work of Theodor Adorno, who used it to describe "ob-
 jects to which the observer no longer has a vital relationship and
 which are in the process of dying."4 This is in part owing to the strain
 of the museum's founding fiction, that an arrangement of heteroge-
 neous objects can constitute a logically consistent representation of
 the world. For the museum, as Donato has remarked, depends on
 an archeological epistemology: it requires the artifacts it displays at
 once to be original and collectively to explain the meaning of a larger
 history.5
 No history presents a greater challenge to the museum in France
 than that of the two world wars. Arguably the defining events of the
 twentieth century, they have also occupied-the Great War until very
 recently, World War II still-a powerful if disquieting place in the
 living memory of the French. Three of the most prominent museums
 devoted to the world wars in France thus offer a fertile terrain for
 an exploration of the museological construction of history and mem-
 ory: the Memorial de Verdun, opened in 1967; the Memorial-Musee
 de la Paix in Caen, inaugurated in 1988 and devoted to the Sec-
 ond World War; and the Historial de la Grande Guerre in Peronne,
 which opened in 1992. These institutions, which I, for convenience,
 label "war museums," fit easily into Nora's category of self-conscious
