 War museums, like most museums that see their role in terms of
 a history construed as scientific rather than commemorative, begin
 with a different set of assumptions. Such institutions espouse the view
 that, whatever the intrinsic interest or visual power of the objects it
 displays, the museum needs to communicate its own message through
 a variety of textual means. This is hardly surprising, but what needs
 to be stressed here is the way in which this view implicitly associ-
 ates objects and memories. "Every passion borders on the chaotic,"
 Walter Benjamin has written, "but the collector's passion borders on
 the chaos of memories." "I The organizers of historical museums fear
 that, in the absence of explicit, text-based orientation, visitors will
 experience the museum, and especially what Michael Baxandall has
 called "the space between object and label," asjust this sort of chaos:'2
 Every war museum, then, begins with a conception of "memory"
 as something to be both used and tamed. Objects can trigger memory
 in Proustian ways, which is to say unpredictably: yet if memory, in this
 view, consists of an assemblage of images personal to each viewer,
 it has enough common elements to be construed as collective. Con-
 strued both as the mass of heterogeneous objects the museum needs
 to arrange and as the familiar ordering system that visitors bring
 with them, memory is the material each museum attempts to trans-
 form into history. In so doing, war museums constantly re-produce,
 in their own terms, one of the museum's fundamental dynamics. To
 cite Donato once again, "the Museum .. . testifies to an archeological
 memory that cannot be recovered except through fabulation," or, to
 use a more current English term, emplotment.'3
 History, in other words, is the plot that weaves together the
