 In light of these claims, it is instructive to begin with an institu-
 tion that anticipated them by half a century. The first major institu-
 tion dedicated to both documenting and exhibiting the history of a
 war in France was founded in 1917 as the Bibliotheque et musee de
 la guerre, which originated in a collection of documents and artifacts
 related to the war assembled by a wealthy Paris industrialist, Henri
 Leblanc, and his wife. Housed in the Cha'teau de Vincennes from
 1925 until its partial destruction in a bombing raid during World
 War II, it is today called the Bibliotheque de documentation interna-
 tionale contemporaine and includes a research library at Nanterre
 and a museum at the Invalides.'7 Because the museum now devotes
 its very limited display space to temporary exhibitions drawn from
 the range of twentieth-century history, its current museological prac-
 tice falls outside the scope of this article, but the initial self-definition
 of the institution had much in common with those of its later counter-
 parts.
 In its original installation in the Leblancs' apartment (and some
 adjoining ones) on the avenue Malakoff (fig. 1), the Bibliotheque-
 musee evinced some of the charm of a private collection. Though the
 ordering hand of the professional staff hired to assist the Leblancs
 manifests itself in the numbered volumes, presumably albums or
 catalogues, their unexpected juxtaposition with model airplanes,
 posters, framed documents and figurines suggests, if not Benjamin's
 "chaos of memories," at least his "magic circle" of private acqui-
 sition.'8 The Leblancs' conception of their collection clearly linked
 memory with documentation. In 1916 Henri Leblanc described their
 vision in these terms: "Durant des siecles, on pourra venir chez nous
 se rememorer les gloires et les horreurs de cet immense conflit, on
