 Magnified by their assumption, explicit or effective, of a memorial
 role, war museums deploy this power on their visitors, seeking to
 channel visitors' memories along the lines of the institution's guiding
 narrative. Through their various display strategies, museum narra-
 tives offer visitors a collective identity to which their own memories of
 the museum will henceforth connect them. I do not mean to suggest
 that museums' strategies are invariably undemocratic; they may well,
 and at Peronne by and large they do, both represent the consensus of
 the latest historical scholarship and seek to promote further discus-
 sion. This openness, however, does not diminish museums' power,
 which stems directly from their institutional need to invest objects
 with a coherent meaning, typically in the form of a story, which their
 visitors can assimilate and, in so doing, ratify. Clearly the Historial's
 explicit message, which involves both the trauma and the ruptural
 effects of war for a transnational European community, resonates
 with its visitors. But Caen's vague internationalism, and Verdun's
 portrait of individual sacrifice for the nation, a theme that emerges
 over and above some pan-European gestures in its guidebook, may
 do so as well.
 As Kirshenblatt-Gimblett has noted, "The museum effect works
 both ways. Not only do ordinary things become special when placed
 in museum settings, but the museum experience itself becomes a
 model for experiencing life outside its walls."66 This claim, that life
 itself can be experienced within the discursive space of the museal,
 has much to do with the privileged position museums occupy in the
 postmodern economy of memory. That economy involves consump-
 tion on at least two levels. On one level, different regions and commu-
 nities engage in vigorous if unacknowledged competition with each
