 counter the pre-eminence of Verdun in standard French accounts
 of World War I, the historians involved with the Historial project
 vaunted both the international character of the battle of the Somme
 and the international scope of the museum as crucial to their work-
 and, as the press noted, as potential attractions for visitors.67 While
 decrying the notion of competition with Peronne as "indecent," the
