 better evidence of such a "finding" than objects presented as artifacts
 of the "real"? The meaning attached to such artifacts is, of course,
 constructed by narrative, but the power of the institution naturalizes
 it, rooting it in objects as a kind of inherence.
 But the divergent public responses to the institutions discussed
 in this article suggest some of the risks that an uncritical embrace
 of the museal poses for historians, as well as the possibilities of
 another, more interrogative approach. The tremendous popularity
 of the Caen Memorial provides a warning, if any were needed, that
 historians cannot compete with spectacle, and that a commodified
 history is all too easily absorbed into spectacle's technologies. On the
 other hand, the resurgence of memory in responses to the Histo-
 rial can, as I have argued, be taken as a sign of the resistance that
 historical discourse may prompt when it allies itself too closely to
 the ordering strategies of the museum. The critic Andreas Huyssen
 proposes an alternative. For Huyssen, the materiality of objects in
 museums offers them the opportunity to make a connection to the
 past that counters the factitious simultaneity promoted by contempo-
 rary media, but only if they remain open to the "multiple discourses
 of memory" in postmodern culture.76 Historians, while not surren-
 dering our critical skills, can benefit from a similar openness. As both
 a discursive formation and a flourishing economy, memory invites us
 to investigate, to question, and in some instances perhaps even to wel-
 come the impact of other cultural forms, including, besides museum
 displays, film, television, and what we conventionally call "fiction," on
 our own practice.
